<HEADLINE>
A would-be great novel, ruined by the last three chapters (CONTAINS SPOILERS)
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<POST>
<POSTER> insomn...@panix.com.invalid (Insomniac) </POSTER>
<POSTDATE> 2007-07-26T07:55:00 </POSTDATE>
The first thirty-four chapters of DH are brilliant, breath-catching,
emotionally-charged, full of struggles between beliefs and doubts,
moral choices between personal and social values, and Orwellian
terror.  As I read it, I was deeply delighted that Rowling had
finally created a novel that transcends what appeared to be a
recreational reading for young kids.  However, after Harry walked
into his self-sacrifice and fell, the following chapters suddenly
changes to a totally different tone.  The final three chapters of
DH are simply a farce!

Piecing evidences from many sources, DH skillfully portrays Dumbledore
as a flawed patriarch, and Harry was left with nothing but his own
moral compass to make his ultimate decision.  That was an existential
moment.  And the end of the chapter is the climax of the whole
book.  But the subsequent King's Cross scene, seemingly a cheap
rip-off of &quot;2001: A Space Odyssey,&quot; simply flushes the quality of
the book down the tube.  Once again, everything was either as
planned or as predicted.  The long boring chats are redundant,
verbose, and simply unbearable.  But that is nothing compared with
next chapter's hour-long debates between Harry and Voldemort while
they circle each other before launching the final blow to kill each
other!  Who cares which side the late Snape was on--we are dueling
to kill now!  That wand succession rule was also contrived and
borderline nonsensical.  What's wrong with the British authors?
Look at action scenes from other cultures: In American Westerns,
two gunmen staring each other silently and unemotionally, quick
draw and firing, and the fight concluded; in Japanese samurai
movies, two swordsmen gazing each other intensely with hands on
the handles of the blades, thunder-like fast withdrawal and slashing,
and the loser tumbled.  Then we have the qunitessential British
action movies--the 007 series, the worst example of the talking
villain syndrome.  Disgusting.

If you don't feel the final battle is a farce, consider this: Molly
Weasley defeated and killed Bellatrix while all other Order members
couldn't even beat her?  Come on!  And what is the stupid scene of
getting everyone rushing to Hogwarts to participate the last battle?
This is like a 1950 Hollywood production in which the calvary or
whatever came at the end to trample the bad guys (and the audience
applaud in the theatre).  That Kreacher scene was particularly
indicative of the fact that the tone of the ending has turned into
a farce.  Oi, it's the grand finale--shop keepers, student parents,
everyone--get on stage, now!   Well at least she didn't throw the
Dudleys or the Muggle Prime Minister into the fight, thank goodness!
Maybe she hurried to finish the book, maybe she ran out of ideas,
or maybe this was her intention--a comical ending.  A would-be
great novel was ruined.  What a shame.
</POST>
