I also thought Molly finishing of Bellatrix was, even if emotional, less
than believable.

The King's Cross chapter is essential, otherwise crucial explanations and
clarifications become impossible.

More than anything else, the entire Harry Potter series is a complex tale of
how Dumbledore planned the destruction of Voldemort. The foreground story
is of Harry studying, playing Quidditch, etc., but meanwhile, silently,
Dumbledore has been researching the secret behind Voldemort's apparent
immortality, hunting for the Horcruxes, teaching Harry crucial lessons,
recruiting Snape and supporting him in his double-agent role, reforming the
Order and a myriad other things, all with the aim of helping Harry fulfill
the Prophecy.

In this sense, the King's Cross chapter is, so to speak, Dumbledore's &quot;final
explanation&quot;.

Actually I was more disappointed in the epilogue than in any of the actual
chapters of the book.
