Most people found this scene to be superficially similar to
a scene from The Matrix series.  Upon slightly deeper
reading, it's obviously allegorical.  But there's something
of a twist, in that it's actually all in Harry Potter's mind.
It's not really Dumbledore in Harry's dream, but Rowling
makes this unobvious in order to plant one last misdirection.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt;  Once again, everything was either as
&gt; planned or as predicted.
">

No, there was literally a &quot;flaw in the plan&quot;.  At the time
of King's Cross, Harry's subconscious incorrectly guessed
at what the flaw was--and this was reflected in what
Dumbledore of his dream said.  But Harry figured out
the truth by the time of his final confrontation with
Voldemort.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt;  The long boring chats are redundant,
&gt; verbose, and simply unbearable.  But that is nothing compared with
&gt; next chapter's hour-long debates between Harry and Voldemort while
