You totally missed the point of Harry's debate with
Voldemort.  It had nothing to do with Snape, or even
the details of Elder Wand succession.  Regardless of
the Elder Wand, Harry Potter had already won.
Voldemort, who had already been horribly afraid of
Harry Potter, knew he was defeated and trapped,
and it was all he could do to keep up a brave face.
He didn't really need to know all the details--he knew
that he had just failed to kill Harry Potter even with
the most powerful wand in history and with a helpless
Harry Potter who didn't even try to fight back.  He
KNEW he was beaten, and he KNEW Harry Potter
was about to kill him, and he was utterly terrified
of it!  From his perspective, Harry Potter was just
toying with his prey--as he himself had done so many
times in the past.

But Harry Potter wasn't just toying with Voldemort.
Harry Potter was trying to save Voldemort's soul,
to whatever extent was possible.  THAT was the
point of his lengthy debate.  Harry Potter wanted
Voldemort to show some remorse--the only thing
which could at least bind his rendered soul back
together.

You might protest, as Ron did, that it's not much
of a consolation that your soul is whole if you're
dead anyway.  Hermione's retort can be taken
as the final word on that question.

