Harry becomes more *powerful* when he's agitated and puts his emotions
behind a spell, but he doesn't become more *skilled*. Power is largely
a matter of strength of will and ability to focus, whereas skill
depends more on intelligence (to learn spells correctly) and dedicated
practice. When Harry was desperate to save Sirius at the end of
&quot;Prisoner of Azkaban,&quot; he was able to cast a whopper of a Patronus
Charm -- a single spell that he had already learned how to do -- by
putting the full force of his will and emotions behind it. Harry has a
powerful will, and hence can be a powerful wizard whose magic has huge
effects. However, emotional agitation doesn't help him learn spells or
perform more skillfully in complicated situations. When he needed to
use the summoning charm to fight the dragon in &quot;Goblet of Fire,&quot; he
had to learn it from Hermione and practice it painstakingly. His
emotions about the task didn't help him. Similarly, when he was
enraged at Snape at the end of &quot;Half-Blood Prince,&quot; his dueling
performance was poor. His heightened emotions didn't help him shoot
straight or cast a nonverbal spell successfully; if anything, they
hindered him.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; There is hardly anything that could motivate a parent to extreme
&gt; emotional involvement more than seeing someone trying to kill one of
&gt; their children.
">

Yes, but as I've tried to point out several times in this thread, the
effects of an epinephrine flood are primitive. You might be able to
perform unexpected feats of strength, run extra fast, or ignore a
painful injury, but you won't be able to play chess better, beat a
tennis champion, or win a fencing match against an expert.

Joe Ramirez
