Based on what Voldemort said just before killing Snape,
Harry incorrectly thought that Snape was the master
of the Elder Wand, and that when Voldemort killed Snape
he became the new master of the Elder Wand.  This would
make sense to Voldemort, because for him defeating
someone always means killing him.  Snape killed
Dumbledore, therefore Snape defeated Dumbledore,
therefore Snape was the master of the Elder Wand.
He killed Snape, therefore he defeated Snape, therefore
he was now the master of the Elder Wand.

Harry's peek into Snapes memories revealed a new
piece of evidence--that Dumbledore conspired with
Snape for Snape to kill him.  Harry put two and two
together and figured that if Dumbledore meant for
Snape to kill him, that therefore Dumbledore meant
Snape to become the new master of the Elder Wand.

Thus, the dream Dumbledore admitted that his plan
was for Snape to become master of the Elder Wand.
This is something the real Dumbledore wouldn't have
admitted, of course, because it wasn't true.  But that's
what Harry's slow-witted brain figured at the time
(this theory actually makes no sense for several
reasons, but Harry never was quick on the uptake).

According to this false premise, the flaw in the plan
was that Voldemort might figure it out and kill
Snape.  This line of thinking directly leads into
questions which reveal how stupid the false premise
was.  To wit:

If Dumbledore meant Snape to become the master
of the Elder Wand, then surely he would have at least
told Snape something about the Elder Wand.

If Snape knew something about the Elder Wand, then
surely he would have taken at least some minimal
measures to prevent Voldemort from getting his
hands on it.  He had months as Headmaster of
Hogwarts during which he could have planted a fake,
just like the fake Griffindor sword.

No, the theory that Dumbledore meant Snape to
become master of the Elder Wand falls apart upon
anything beyond the most superficial examination.
Still, Harry's kind of dumb, so it usually takes him
months to figure out this sort of thing.  It's
uncharacteristically clever of him to work it out
in such a short time.

