Well, I *do* think she's a badass prior to the duel, but you brushed
my reasons aside (everyone's scared of her, even, to some extent
dumbledore, and she's clever etc., and she's very protective). Even if
she's merely a domineering &quot;force of nature&quot;, I'm not sure that
matters. I also demonstrated that she had a lot of motivation - the
loss of her brothers, and the loss of one of her sons. She has 8
people she'd die to protect, and Bella only 1.

You on the other hand, basically suggested that she couldn't possibly
be a good duellist because she's just a housewife.  You also suggested
that duelling was a highly skilled sport, but you fail to demonstrate
how Bellatrix got so good given that she just spent 15 years in prison
without a wand or the ability to practice.  So that suggests to me
that there's a LOT more to it than &quot;skill&quot;.

Since neither of us can demonstrate with any certainty where EITHER
woman would have picked up their skills (though from a logical
standpoint, if practice *is* important, it seems to me that Molly is
more likely to have been motivated to practice over the years, given
her protectiveness and children, and assumption that V would come back
some day, whereas Bella was in prison for most of it, plus had a sense
of hubris that would have made her think she didn't need to practice
as she already knew she was a badass). And if being a good duelist
isn't solely from practice and skill, then well, Molly's force of
nature personality and protective mother-bearishness might be enough
to make her better. Plus she wasn't crazy, or had a sence of hubris.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; Obviously, it's impossible to prove that Molly was *not* privately
&gt; honing her dueling skills by practicing for years, since so little of
&gt; her life is described in the novels. So if you prefer to assume that
&gt; training was going on behind the scenes, fine. I'm just saying that
&gt; there is no direct textual support for such an assumption, because
&gt; there isn't.
">

True. But neither is there textual support that Bellatrix could have
gotten good either. Like Molly, she just *was* good, and you don't
seem to have trouble believing that.  The first time she dueled, you
accepted that she was a badass, with no textual support for that,
either.

<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
&gt; &gt; &gt; There is no evidence or suggestion of that in the novels. All we saw
&gt; &gt; &gt; was a Molly Weasley whose anxieties for her family prevented her from
&gt; &gt; &gt; even dispatching a boggart properly.

&gt; &gt; There's a BIG difference between dispatching a relatively harmless
&gt; &gt; boggart, than being in the line of fire of one of the more powerful
&gt; &gt; witches in the world.

&gt; So because Molly failed at the easy task, she was more likely to
&gt; succeed at the difficult task? :)
">

Well, yes, actually, but not in the way you just stated it. When you
KNOW you are dealing with a harmless boggart that can't hurt you in
the least, then it's OK to break down and cry when you see the bodies
of your sons, especially when you know that it's not real.  In other
words she had nothing to lose in that situation.

On the other hand, when your life and the lives of your children
REALLY ARE threatened, you are much more likely to actually ACT.
Because the alternative is devestating.

Here's a real life example that I think might demonstrate what I
mean.  I'm a mother. I have a 5 year old daughter.  When I see stories
about parent's losing their children, I cry.  Totally weepy.  Kind of
embarassingly so.  When my husband and I wrote our will, I cried.  On
the other hand, when I think she's in danger, I ACT.  I hear a big
thump from upstairs, I don't start crying, I dart up the stairs and go
see if she needs help.  When I held her up so she could see over the
railing, I do it, but clutch her tight, so she won't fall.    One
time, I saw a baby (not my own) start to fall off a chair in the
waiting room at the doctor's office, and I dived across the aisle,
bruised up both knees, but caught the little girls before she hit the
floor.  When my stepson was a toddler, he fell off a coffee table and
bit his tongue and had blood POURING out of his mouth. My husband
broke down slightly in his panic, but I didn't. I made the decision
that we were heading to the hospital, got them into the car and drove
like a bat out of hell to the ER.  So despite my being an emotional
wreck at the IDEA of children dying or suffering, when push comes to
shove, I rise to the occasion when need be. I think this is a common
phenomenon.

Either way, I think you've decided that it was unrealistic of Molly
Weasily to be good enough to defeat Bellatrix, and I doubt that
anything I have to say will change your mind.  Correct?

Cathy Weeks
